segments.text: Okay, in the interest of humility and knowledge, I'm asking you to donate this tape to me or to the Texas A&M oral history collection in the University Archives.
Is this okay with you?
The topic is going to be the 1960s counterculture and the social movements at Colorado State University.
Please briefly describe your education and your upbringing.
Well, I was raised Protestant fundamentalist in Colorado.
Attended school, mostly in religious school.
Got my bachelor's degree from Southern Nazarene University.
And after that, I spent some time in the Army.
And after that, went back to school and got my master's at Colorado College and my PhD at the University of Illinois.
Okay.
I didn't really plan to do anything with it vocationally until I got back out of the Army and then discovered I could get a PhD.
And if I did that, I could teach at the college level.
And so that made it possible for the first time to make a living doing philosophy.
What was so interesting about philosophy to you?
Oh, I think the traditional things that interest people in philosophy.
meaning of life?
Why are we here?
Those are the kinds of questions that got me interested in philosophy.
Okay.
Which, of course, are the questions philosophy cannot answer, but I didn't know that then.
Right.
When and where did you teach during the 1960s?
Well, 1956 to 50,
I went from 57 to 67.
I taught at Colorado State University.
And then from 67 on here at Texas A&M.
What influenced your decisions to become a teacher?
I think I always like to share ideas.
But what I got and I came to like about it was the fact that you can see people share these ideas and appreciate these ideas.
I guess what motivates you to teach is the fact that some people seem to learn something.
Okay, this is where we get to the good stuff.
What was the attitude and the spirit of the students when you began teaching, and did you witness a change as the decade of the 60s progressed?
Yeah, in the late 50s.
That's when I was a student and when I first started teaching.
This was a very fearful period.
This is a period of McCarthyism, and I think people today don't really understand how strong that influence was.
because even as late as 57 at Colorado College, which was a private school, there was a McCarthy Club, students and faculty.
And it was well known that they monitored the teaching and the comments of other people.
And this was also the period of loyalty oaths, that in order to get a teaching job, you had
in the Constitution of the United States.
So it was a period in the late 50s when people were so afraid of communism that this allowed people like McCarthy and others to dominate the intellectual life of this country.
And people literally would not say or publish certain things because they were afraid they might get investigated.
And it wasn't just being communist.
If you were a member of the American Civil Liberties Union, it was something considered to be beyond the pale.
During that period of time, an attitude which George Bush has revived.
It was anti-paternalism was really how it started out.
These kids didn't like what their parents were doing.
They didn't like the way their parents lived.
They didn't like their parents' focus on making money.
They thought there should be something more important in life than fighting communism and making money.
They didn't know what it was, and so what they turned to was,
folk music, drugs, turning off, Tim Leary said, turning off, turning on, doing your own thing.
Community living was big then.
Groups of students would live together in old houses and share their food, share their belongings.
out with some new values, knowing that the old values were bad, but they had no clear idea whatsoever what they were going to replace the old values with.
They were anti-system, anti-establishment.
They knew that was bad.
They didn't know what was good.
They didn't know how to replace it.
That, I think, characterized the 60s.
Now, some people took political advantage of this, and there were some movements organized
And I think the leaders of these movements, like the Students for Democratic Society, maybe they had a particular agenda.
But I think most of the people that followed these various movements were simply drifting around, looking for something better.
Peace and love and so on.
And during this period, I had the reputation on campus of being a conservative at Colorado State University.
Because I would argue with these kids, and I would say, all right, now, what is it you want?
Be positive.
You say, this is bad.
Don't you have an obligation?
was too clear.
Then, of course, also during that period, this all got caught up in the anti-Vietnam War, too.
They were against the war in Vietnam.
And I think that movement, that group of young people who just didn't like what was going on, they were
there to be used and directed by any number of people.
But generally, they were quickly disillusioned by the people who were using them and directing them.
These people never went far enough as far as the young people were concerned.
And in a way, it was sad because there was a lot of idealism
And there wasn't any leadership.
There wasn't anybody to direct it in any positive direction.
See, and all you could tell them was something like, well, stay within the system.
Work within it.
Try to change it from within.
And they would have no part of that.
They weren't interested in doing that because they figured if you worked within the system, you simply got corrupted by the system.
And they may have been right about that.
But they weren't willing to destroy the system.
They didn't have...
really proved.
Then this movement stopped because nobody really wanted to get shot.
And so it was repressed by the government eventually.
Did some of the classes you teach reflect your attitudes and views or the views of the 60s?
No, I didn't go in for relevant classes, although I always taught existentialism.
And a lot of these people thought they were existentialists.
They claimed an affinity with existentialism.
And I try to point out to them, well, they really weren't existentialists.
They were just half-baked existentialists.
They wanted to do their own thing.
But existentialism always says, if you do your own thing, you must assume responsibility for it.
They didn't want to do that.
They didn't want to assume any responsibility for their actions, no matter what their actions were.
They were parasites in a way.
They wanted the freedom to use the society to have, you know, do drugs, dissent, rebel.
But they wanted society always there to be to catch them if they fell or if they made a mistake.
So that's why I say it was anti-paternalism.
Most of this movement was getting even with mom and dad and yet hoping that mom and dad would be there
to pick up the pieces if things got out of hand.
You always know they'll be there if you need them.
I think they really always counted on that, you see.
And for the most part, that's what happened.
The parents were there and picked them up.
And I think most of the parents were supportive, ultimately supportive.
So when people talked about it as being a great political revolution or a
Sexual revolution or drug revolution.
I think those were side issues.
Those were symptoms.
They would engage in certain activity, mainly because it irritated their parents.
And what activity would they select?
What will irritate your parents?
I remember talking to a young girl I had in class.
I still know her.
We're still friends.
But she was a very attractive girl, except she didn't care for her parents.
She'd wear old clothes and
Her hair was never combed and she looked dirty and so on.
And I asked her one day, I said, you know, why the devil don't you clean up?
I said, why do you dress like that?
She said, well, because, because of my parents.
And I said, why?
She said, well, they always want me to be neat and clean.
And I said, so you're not going to be neat and clean because your parents want you to be.
Yeah, that's right.
That's right.
So, you know, it's a way of trying to shock her parents.
But she still, you know, she never really left her parents.
They never really left her.
This was a, it was almost a bloodless revolution.
I mean, and I think displaying in some ways because it never really accomplished a great deal.
Most of what happened was bad.
You got some people who got really hooked on bad drugs.
You got some people who really lost their purpose in life, became drifters.
Oh, some good music came out.
But it was strictly a made-in-the-USA kind of rebellion.
safely within limits and boundaries, I think, never really got out of hand.
And I think the government overreacted by starting to shoot people.
And that's why, if these people had been serious, they would have shot back.
But they weren't.
It was just kind of like, oh,
Some of the classes you taught, were there guidelines?
Were you able to set your own goals or guidelines for your classes, or was the administration really strict on what you were allowed to teach and how you were supposed to teach it?
You know, after the 50s were over, we got rid of McCarthyism.
You had a great deal of freedom in the classroom because during the 60s,
You had teach-ins, big thing.
You had a lot of professors using the classroom to support the students, to support various causes, all of which I thought was bad.
I thought that was a misuse of the classroom.
But you had the counterpart of that was you had, in many places, students taking over classrooms, trying to take over universities.
And that's what upset me.
I think that's finally what upset the academic world, was that students weren't playing the game anymore.
We'll let you have our classroom.
We'll talk about these issues.
But when you try to run the university, no, we won't let you do that.
And did you encourage them to be active and offer advice?
Well, yes, I did.
I did.
It depends what you mean.
Encourage them to be active.
I try to keep from hurting themselves.
I tried to get them to avoid excesses if I could.
And in fact, one time, I can't remember the exact years, but there was a period where students were experimenting with LSD.
They were getting it from certain varieties of morning glory seeds, which contained it naturally.
Lysergic acid contained it naturally.
But they didn't know how to use it.
They didn't know how to get it from the morning glory seeds, how to use it.
They didn't know what precautions to take.
And this was a time where LSD was a recreational drug.
It was almost like whiskey.
I mean, professors, students were using it.
People were spending the weekend.
putting drops of LSD on sugar cubes, dripping them down, and having trips.
And so you'd get some kids that, to use the language of that day, kids that would really freak out, I mean.
And we began to learn some things about drugs.
Learned one, that you could set the mood by setting the stage.
In other words, if a person prepared themself,
by reading certain things, talking about certain things, then they would have a certain kind of drug experience.
But that drug experience wasn't very stable, that you needed to have somebody around that kept it within bounds by talking to them holding their hand and so on.
People shouldn't use drugs on their own.
We learned that because people would jump out of windows and kill themselves.
We learned also that
If people had any psychotic tendencies at all, and they might not be obvious on the surface, the drugs would bring it out, especially LSD would bring it out.
And so people would just sometimes go permanently around the bend because of the LSD when they might have lived a normal life without using the LSD.
So people fairly quickly got scared of LSD because of so-called bad trips.
But during that period of experimentation, I remember...
typing up and reproducing a little one-page instruction on how to use morning glory seeds so that the kids would not have bad trips, see?
And these instructions were printed later in the college newspaper.
You know, imagine the battalion doing this.
And kids would recount their trips, their acid trips.
They'd write them up in paper.
I mean, this was all open.
I mean, nobody was saying, this is bad stuff.
People were saying, well, keep it under control.
It's totally different from the day with the gist, they know.
Oh, yeah.
It really was a period of, as I say, experimentation.
And I had kids come to class and light up a joint marijuana, and I finally made them stop that.
I just said, no, you don't know.
And so I think the students' graduate award in LSD was bad.
And I remember having in class debates about marijuana.
And you'd have some students say, oh, it's all right, and other students say, no, it's bad.
And this was not on moral grounds at all.
I mean, these are kids who tried it and said, you know, all the time I was on it, I didn't care about anything.
You just don't care.
You know, you don't do any harm, particularly.
You don't go out and kill people, but you just don't care about anything.
You're passing.
And we have arguments like this.
But in this pamphlet, I start to tell you about, you know, the seeds, the morning glory seeds, certain varieties had LSD in them, or resurgic acid in them.
So first you had to wash the seeds carefully.
Then you had to grind them up.
Because some kids would take a handful of seeds, nothing would happen.
They'd take another handful and nothing would happen.
And then all of a sudden, finally, the seeds were being broken down by their digestive juices and they'd get hit with these massive doses of seed.
So what you had to do was grind it up so that you'd get the effect quickly.
And then the right amount
have a friend there and, you know, do all this because it's necessary to have at least two people around.
I thought with LSD, because you might hurt yourself just thinking you could walk into a mirror or all kinds of stupid things.
I never used any of the drugs myself during that period.
And, but I did try, I guess that's just,
political side of it, too.
You hated to see him get shot.
You hated to see him confront the police because you knew, ultimately, what the attitude or authority was going to be.
And these things came to a head, I think, with Kent State and the Democratic Convention in Chicago.
Basically, the grown-ups said, this is enough.
If we have to, we'll shoot you.
Did you encourage debates in your class regarding student rights, women's rights, civil rights in the Vietnam War?
Yeah, sure did.
We talked a lot about student rights.
And we had quite a few debates about the war.
This was common during that period.
I was generally a person, if they had a debate, I generally argued for
who were in Vietnam.
And the reason for that was is that they were all against it.
They didn't think about the other side of the issue at all.
And I think if I had been in Korean War, and I think if I had been of age, I would have gone to Vietnam.
I would have thought that's my job.
But they didn't think that way.
about women's rights.
Civil rights is already past, you know, it's getting going.
Well, women's rights came very late.
It's a funny thing.
See, these people didn't care about women's rights.
The kids in the 60s used women.
And these communes that have, there's usually one woman who did all the work.
She cooked all the food.
She took care of everybody.
And that's what held the thing together.
And if she quit, if she got tired of doing this, you know, she was the earth mother figure.
If she quit doing this, the thing would fall apart.
But these kids used one.
Women weren't considered to be equal in the 60s.
That movement didn't have anything to do with women's rights.
Now, it tried to latch up with the racial movement.
It tried to.
But I think most of them admitted afterward they really didn't care about that issue either.
That was just something to do.
It was a cause.
See, these were people looking for something to do, something to give their life meaning, right?
And whatever, you know, whatever they could latch up to would work, but women's rights was not one of the things they got up to.
They got into civil rights movement, anti-war movement, pro-drug movement, you know, sex, pre-sex.
Pre-sex was a big issue.
And freedom of speech was a big issue, which meant, you know,
Really, what that meant at that time was that you could say, fuck, without getting in trouble.
That was the free speech issue.
You might have said that you did some participation with your students taking the counter side to what they talked about.
How did your administration view your participation?
Well, I think the students thought I was a conservative, and the administration thought I was a communist.
kind of stuck in the middle.
Yeah, because as long as you were doing anything with this student movement, then the administration didn't like it.
But the students, and some of them told me afterwards, they said, you know, you were the guy we had to test our ideas against.
We had some ideas that we thought were really liberal
They were just nervous.
They were nervous.
They were afraid the students were going to take over the university.
They were going to be destructive and so on and so forth.
And they didn't really understand what the root causes were.
And they could have used this.
They could have used this whole movement as a great educational opportunity.
But they didn't.
They just wanted to shut it down.
How could they have used it as an interesting point?
Well, these students weren't
with these issues.
Now, a lot of teachers did this, but they did it independent of the administration.
I mean, if you said, okay, we're going to have a teach-in about student rise or about war, you had to do this on your own.
The administration didn't like it particularly.
And this is why, you see, this is why ultimately in
It's because they thought the administration was beginning to say certain things cannot be done for educational purposes.
This kind of discussion, we don't want it.
So then the students got more militant.
They said, well, we'll just take over the classroom.
Or if there would be a professor who would be in his classroom and attack them, they might go after him.
Now, I attacked them in my class.
to be fearful objects at all.
I just thought they were misguided.
There was a lot of good stuff.
I mean, there was a lot of this youthful idealism.
But we never took advantage of it, you see.
And it was Kennedy saw something here, you see.
Kennedy tried to channel it with the Peace Corps, you see.
And that helped some.
and helped siphon off some of it, the constructive part of it, you see.
More of that should have been done.
But of course, you see, Kennedy didn't last long enough.
And this was disillusioning.
I think if Kennedy had remained president and been elected for second term, as I think he would have been, I think maybe all of this energy would have been channeled off in a useful direction.
But Kennedy's shot, so what do you think?
Why did they shoot him?
Well, they shot him because he was on our side, you know.
And then who comes in?
A guy who just loved to antagonize the students.
And Dixon says, they did when I do this.
They did.
Were you pressured to publish?
And what kind of materials did you publish in the 60s?
more than anybody else was.
I mean, in the academic world, if you want to get ahead, you have to .
So everybody's pressured.
But there wasn't any particular new or novel kind of pressure in the 60s.
Nor was there any pressure to do anything in any particular way or direction.
It was unusual.
Mostly it was just philosophical stuff, kind of independent of that era.
So much is made of the drug culture in the 1960s, and you've already stated that you witnessed a lot of this.
Do you agree with the assumptions that it increased and expanded the power of the mind with the use of drugs?
I mean, to say that these drugs were consciousness expanding is certain and true because people would have experiences and see things that you normally don't see, okay?
I remember one student coming into my office one day and he was all bloody.
Scratched up, clothed and torn and big smile on his face and I said, what have you been doing?
He said, I had a wonderful trip.
He said, I took this LSD
He said, it came to me that if I could walk to the top of Horsetooth Mountain, that was a mountain near the university, that's probably 15 miles to the top from the university.
He said, if I could walk to the top of that mountain in a straight line, without stopping for anything, he said, the second coming would occur.
He said, I knew that.
line.
He never made it to the top, but he got to the point where he was exhausted and fell asleep.
Then he came back down.
He was sober now.
He's over his drug experience.
He really believed that.
Well, that's a novel kind of experience.
You don't normally believe those kinds of things.
That's why a lot of people use them.
to have.
I don't think so.
I think generally not.
Some of them were very benign experiences.
If you properly conditioned yourself, if you read a lot of Buddhist stuff, then you take LSD and people tell me you had a Buddhist experience.
That was very pleasant to see.
But it didn't last any longer.
The drug influence, the drug lasted.
And there was always a possibility of doing permanent damage to your brain.
So, no, I just don't think it was a good idea.

Now, I don't agree, never have agreed, though, with the government's attitude that every drug from marijuana up in any amount, from the amount on the head for paying up, should put somebody in prison.
I don't agree with that.
There were a lot of people who used LSD in the 60s who never suffered any harmful effects.
They used it, they tried it, they quit it.
There's a lot of people still using marijuana today.
And it seemed to me the drugs of today, the drugs of the 90s and the 80s, like cocaine and crack, are much more deadly, much more deadly than LSD and marijuana and things they had in those days.
So the fact that the government cracked down and tried to control us hasn't accomplished anything.
It hasn't done any good.
And I think maybe we ought to try decriminalizing some of the drugs.
Cocaine, no, I don't think you ought to decriminalize it.
I think marijuana is not helpful to people, but I don't think alcohol is either.
In fact, I think alcohol is more harmful than marijuana.
And I think this is something people have got to make up their own minds about.
So, you know, to answer your question, I don't think the drugs did anybody any good.
I think everybody ought to leave them alone.
But I think that about cigarettes too.

I think nowadays the drug problem is they're trying to get a state of euphoria out of it and a great feeling I think maybe in the 60s they used it to see if they could find something else in their mind or something else that they're just... Well, a lot of them did.
A lot of people used it because they thought this would give them a meaning and purpose in life and so on.
Yeah.
But there were those who did it for the euphoria too.
If you smoke anything, we know now if you smoke something, whether it's crack or cigarettes, it gets into the brain stream very quickly.
If you inject it in your veins, it gets into your blood system quickly, but not as quickly as if you smoke it.
And if you eat it, it takes longer to get into the nervous system.
Now, we also know
that addictions of drugs that you smoke are the hardest ones to overcome.
The needle stuff is the second hardest, and ingestion by mouth is the easiest to overcome.
The quicker it hits your bloodstream, the more addictive it becomes.
Each three types of addiction require different treatment, and each three types of addiction
are types of addiction adopted by people with different personalities.
I think in the 60s, you had a lot of... What's the drug you make cookies out of?
Hashish is one.
You had a lot of people eating drugs in the 60s and swallowing drugs by mouth.
And most of those people could quit.
I did quit while I did quit.
Now, where was the crack?
And the reason it's being marketed is just for money.
The people who supply drugs developed crack.
They sat down and planned this.
Crack, oh boy, this will get them quick.
And this will hook them forever.
And you smoke it, especially.
And you've got them.
So that's a whole different approach to drugs.
And
The government attempts to take care of the drug problem.
We're not affecting the 60s, and they're not affecting them.
I'm not sure what the answer is.
With people with crack cocaine, I don't know what the answer is.
We may have to adopt the Chinese answer.
They gave them six months to get off, and then they shot them.
That's right.
I hate to advocate that, but I don't know that there is a cure.
And it's a terribly hard addiction to overcome, I understand.
But to blame all that on the 60s is ridiculous.
Yeah.
The 1960s was a time of tremendous change.
Were these changes...
Did you witness these changes on your campus and do you believe they were inevitable?
Well, we saw changes.
Let's just talk about the so-called sexual revolution.
What happened in the 60s was that people of college age began sleeping with each other without the benefit of matrimony.
Much to the consternation of their parents.
And the school authorities, for the most part.
And that was a change.
I don't think it was inevitable.
I think the rebellion against parents was probably inevitable.
The 50s were so darn repressive.
that the kids had to rebel at some point.
Now, what form that rebellion took, I guess maybe it had to be a sexual form of some kind.
Maybe it had to be a drug.
I don't think so.
I think that rebellion could have taken other forms.
But it's just hard for me to think that
But that had to happen in any sense of inevitability.
I don't think so.
I think if parents had been a little smarter, if the government had been a little smarter, we wouldn't be sitting here talking about the 60s today.
Colorado has like a reputation of having three spirits.
DC, Boulder, and Colorado State.
Was this evident in the 60s and just continued on until today?

Well, I didn't know it at the time, but yes, you look back and you have to say that Colorado State and Boulder were one of the wilder places in the university scene, because we didn't know that then, like the students knew it then.
It just turned out that way.
And I've often wondered why that's the case.
of states.
So you had a kind of cross-section of America.
I mean, they weren't just Colorado kids.
There aren't that many Colorado kids.
You're kind of in a backwater.
You're in the middle of the nation and you're not strongly influenced by what goes on on either coast.
So you're kind of free.
Free from scrutiny.
Free to develop on your own.
And so nobody was...
When they weren't doing the things that they were doing in Columbia, they were burning buildings around it.
Oh, they did burn one building in CSU.
I think it was an ROTC building.
But they weren't being destructive in the same way.
But also, being in Colorado, there's greater toleration of individualism.
Now, you compare that with Texas A&M.
See, I came down to Texas A&M in 67, and I thought the 60s were practically over.
Well, we got a little bit of the 60s here, but we got it in the late 60s and early 70s.
I mean, we had three people join the SDS here, and we had some marijuana in the dorms, and we had some drugs, and we had a little unrest.
Maybe we had one demonstration against Vietnam, but it was so mild.
I mean...
Texas A&M was in the backwater too, but because it was in the cultural backwater, it wasn't influenced by these things.
But Colorado was influenced because most of the students here were from Texas, but most of the students there were from all over the country.
So they brought in these ideas from all over the country and mixed them up there.
Then you had some people who didn't know what to do about it.
I guess it did turn out to be an interesting place.
Now, Colorado College could turn repressive.
I taught there one year, and what they did at Colorado College is that they expelled any student found using drugs.
Well, at Colorado State, we thought that was terrible.
Because, as I said, there's still people using drugs for writing about it in the school newspaper.
It was just like, you know, I'm trying this new idea, you know.
I don't know why it was that permissive then, compared to other places.
When you came to Texas A&M in 1967, was it, I can't remember when the court was forced to allow it.
Yeah, this is a few years afterward.
But still, most of the students here were male in the court when I came.
And you said you witnessed one, or knew of one, demonstration against Vietnam.
Mm-hmm.
What was the Corps' reaction to that?
Well, the Corps all gathered around these five or six people who were demonstrating and had to be, who had to be protected by the campus police.
Happened right out here in front of Sully Ross, the academic building.
But the campus police just gathered around and let these five or six kids demonstrate for 20 minutes, and then that was it.
This is the way to handle it, I think.
I mean, that's all there were, five or six kids, and most of them were from somewhere else, I think.
There just wasn't any strong anti-war sentiment here, or hippie element here.
Plowed children, no, not at A&M, no.
Did you ever go to visit other campuses like Berkeley or Columbia during the 60s?
What did you visit there?
They were pretty wild, too.
I'd go give talks at the California universities during that period.
And the students would come into the building, and they would be dressed or undressed in all kinds of weird ways.
That was one characteristic.
And they would sit in the windows or on the floors, and they'd have their guitars with them.
And it was kind of like, you know, we're going to have a nanny.
And you either talk their language and communicate with them fairly quickly or you lost them.
It was all superficially very free and easy.
Superficially, that way.
But these kids weren't free and easy inside.
That was the sad part.
They were looking for something and never did find it.
A lot of movies have been made about this.
Like The Big Chill.
I don't know what, you know, about how people reflecting back on their experience.
I think they're quite right when they reflect back and say, you know, what turns out to be finally nice about it is that we were close together and we felt friendly toward each other.
The communal experience was about the only thing that lasted.
Made some friends.
They all had to get jobs sometimes and they had to become part of the system.
And most of them did a very good job at it.
You know, it's interesting.
Look at Tom Hayden.
And who else was I thinking of?
Well, Hayden's a good example of a radical...
Mark Lee was in philosophy.
Angela Davis was a woman who taught philosophy.
A lot of these so-called radicals, leaders, were from philosophy, which is what you'd expect, actually, to think about these things.
But the people that followed them, as I said, didn't really.
Outside of being friends and having a warm, friendly experience,
You know, it didn't make a permanent effect on this country at all.
I could be wrong.
I mean, in a sense, some things happen.
We can't go back.
We can't go back to the 50s again.
That's one good thing the 60s did for us.
We can't go back to McCarthy again.
I don't think.
But see, I don't know.
I see people who want to.
and Jesse Helms and so on remind me of McCarthy a great deal.
